## Communication

- [Less is more][less-is-more]. LLMs generate faster than humans can keep up -- aim for concise, scannable output that aids quick parsing.

## Planning

- Get early feedback on the plan before substantive execution when the task is ambiguous, high-risk, or wide in scope. Otherwise, proceed after only the inspection needed to form a concrete plan.
- Plans must be concise and scannable -- use clean Markdown hierarchy (headings, tables, bullet lists), not dense prose or confusing sub-numbering (eg, `1a`, `1b`).

## Programming & Engineering

- [Less is more][less-is-more] applies to code too -- prefer simple over simplistic, and aim for concise, modular, and elegant code.
- Follow codebase or relevant community conventions and style (eg, Python has [PEP-0008](https://peps.python.org/pep-0008/) and [Zen of Python](https://docs.python.org/3/glossary.html#term-Zen-of-Python)).
- Prefer early-exit guard clauses over nested/spaghetti control flow code.
- Never fail silently; fail loudly with a clear, actionable error.
- Keep logic flat and readable; avoid unnecessary inner helper functions.
- Prefer proven tools over hand-rolled scripts (eg, logrotate for log rotation) -- ideally lightweight and composable tools.
- **Document design decisions at the source**: When a non-obvious architectural or design choice is made (eg, why a specific hook type was chosen, why a naming convention is coupled to another system, why a workaround exists), document the WHY in the source file (docstring, comment, or adjacent README). Never leave a future agent or engineer to rediscover context from git history alone.
- **Python scripts — `uv` shebangs**: Use `#!/usr/bin/env -S uv run` for stdlib-only scripts, `#!/usr/bin/env -S uv run --script` when the script has [PEP 723](https://peps.python.org/pep-0723/) inline dependency metadata. `uv` handles Python version resolution and dependency isolation — no `mise x`, virtualenv, or `pip install` needed. For scripts that must not couple to a project's `pyproject.toml` (eg, hooks that run from the project root), use `--no-project` to prevent `uv` from discovering and parsing project config at startup.
- **Python scripts — module-level docstrings**: Every Python script must include a comprehensive module-level docstring covering intent, architecture/design, and key decision trade-offs. A future reader should understand WHY the script exists and how it fits the larger system without reading git history.
- Comments as code unless explaining a decision or including references
- No dead code
- When no clear, applicable convention or principle exists, prefer:
  - [YAGNI](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/You_aren%27t_gonna_need_it)
  - [SOLID](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SOLID), especially [Single Responsibility Principle](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Single-responsibility_principle)
  - [Separation of Concerns](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Separation_of_concerns)
  - [UNIX Philosophy](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unix_philosophy)
  - [The Pragmatic Programmer](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Pragmatic_Programmer), especially tracer bullets and fixing broken windows
  - [Functional Programming](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Functional_programming), especially the pragmatism of OCaml and F#
  - [The Zen of Python](https://docs.python.org/3/glossary.html#term-Zen-of-Python): explicit, simple, flat, sparse, readable, practical, loud on errors, unambiguous, and easy to explain
  - Avoid [Hungarian Notation](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hungarian_notation)
  - Prefer self-documenting names over terse abbreviations (e.g., `p4changelist` over `cl`); stop before restating the type or implementation in the name
  - snake_case > camelCase
  - Spaces > Tabs
- **Automated functional tests**: When adding or modifying functionality, write automated tests that prevent regressions and document supported features and workflows. Prefer real inputs and outputs over mocks — tests should be as close to actual user behavior as possible. Tests are the durable spec; comments and docstrings supplement but do not replace them.

## Debugging

- Only test one hypothesis/variable at a time unless applying a `git bisect` style strategy.
- For Neovim plugin operations (Lazy update, TSInstall, Mason installs, checkhealth, etc.), prefer `nvim --headless "..." "+qa"` over asking the user to run commands interactively inside Neovim.
- When a repo has `pre-commit` configured, invoke linters and validators via `pre-commit run <hook-id> --all-files` rather than calling the tool binary directly — the binary may not be on `PATH` outside the pre-commit virtualenv. To verify a set of changes, prefer a single `pre-commit run --all-files` (or scoped to touched files) over hand-assembling equivalent checks (eg, `python3 -m json.tool`, `yamllint`, `chezmoi execute-template`); the hooks already cover them.

## Observability & Reliability

- Follow [OpenTelemetry (OTel)](https://opentelemetry.io/docs/index.md) Conventions and Standards.

## Version Control

**git:**

- Follow [conventional commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/en/v1.0.0/): use semantic commit subjects, and include audit-useful rationale/details in the commit body. Also see [Semantic Commit Messages](https://gist.github.com/joshbuchea/6f47e86d2510bce28f8e7f42ae84c7106).
- Auto-proceed on read-only git operations (`status`, `diff`, `log`, `show`, `branch`, `pull`, `push`, `push --force-with-lease`, etc.) without asking.
- Push immediately after every commit in the same turn — do not wait to be asked.
- Outside plan mode (implementation / "accept edits" mode): auto-commit completed work without asking. The user's workflow is: plan mode for design/decision alignment, then implementation mode where commits should flow automatically. Do not pause to ask "should I commit?" after making changes. Exception: if implementation uncovers a fundamental design issue or requires a new significant design/decision, pause and return to plan mode for alignment before continuing. Also pause (do not auto-commit) when the user corrects or pushes back on a recent change — fix the code and wait for explicit commit instruction.
- Always pause before destructive or hard-to-reverse operations (`push --force`, `push --delete`, `rebase`, `reset`, `stash pop/drop`, `tag`) unless the user has explicitly requested that action in the current message.
- **Pull-rebase-before-push**: Always `git pull --rebase` immediately before `git push`. If push is still rejected (non-fast-forward), retry once with `git pull --rebase && git push` before surfacing an error.
- **Named stashes**: Always `git stash push -m "<unique-slug>"` — never bare `git stash`. Pop by name (`git stash list` + `git stash pop stash@{n}` matching the slug). Multiple agents share the stash stack; unnamed stashes will collide.
{{- if .isRiotMachine }}
- **P4 workflow**: See the `p4-workflow` skill for Perforce changelists, workspace isolation, sync, submit, and broken-build recovery rules.
{{- end }}

## Workflow

**todo.txt:**

- If `todo.txt` or `done.txt` don't exist at the repo root, create them (`touch todo.txt done.txt`).
- Use `todo.sh` commands for all `todo.txt`/`done.txt` operations; fall back to direct file read/edit only when the CLI is not installed.

**Multi-instance worktrees (MANDATORY):**

Concurrent agents on the same branch create file-edit races (last write wins). Every session that modifies files MUST use an isolated git worktree — on Claude Code, Write/Edit/Bash mutations are hook-blocked until inside one.

  1. `git pull`, then check existing claims: `todo.sh list @worktree`.
  2. On Claude Code: `EnterWorktree name: "$CLAUDE_CODE_SESSION_ID.<task-slug>"`. On other tools: `git worktree add .worktrees/<session-id>.<task-slug> -b task/<session-id>.<task-slug>` then `cd` into it.
  3. Record in `todo.txt`: `@worktree:.claude/worktrees/<session-id>.<task-slug>`, `session:<id>`, `agent:<tool>`, `model:<full-model-id>`. Commit this entry as part of the worktree's first commit — `todo.sh` mutations are blocked on main, so the entry must be committed here to survive the merge-back.

  Example: `(B) Fix auth bug +api @worktree:.claude/worktrees/b9395dee.auth-fix session:b9395dee agent:claude model:claude-vertex/anthropic-claude-sonnet-4-6-default`

  On completion (Claude Code): while still **inside** the worktree: run `todo.sh do <task-id>` and commit the change. If main has advanced since branching, run `git rebase main` to linearise the branch so `--ff-only` succeeds. Then `ExitWorktree action: remove`, `git merge --ff-only <worktree-branch>`, `git branch -d <worktree-branch>`, and push. The bash guard allows `--ff-only` specifically for this merge-back pattern. On other tools: merge to main, `git worktree remove .worktrees/<session-id>.<task-slug>`, and delete the branch.

  **Auto-cleanup:** The Stop hook removes merged worktrees for the current session and archives their `todo.txt` entries. Prefer explicit `ExitWorktree` — the hook is a safety net, not a substitute.

  Human-only bypass: `touch .claude/worktree-exempt.$CLAUDE_CODE_SESSION_ID`. Agents must never use this.

**Pane label:** As soon as the task is identifiable (even before a worktree or todo.txt entry exists), write a short summary to `~/.claude/task-labels/$TMUX_PANE` and run `tmux select-pane -T "label"`. Guard with `[[ -n "${TMUX:-}" ]] &&`. Update as understanding improves; sync to the todo.txt task slug when one is created. The `UserPromptSubmit` hook auto-labels from the raw user prompt; agent refinements override it and persist across subsequent user messages.

## (Code) Reviews

Reviewer thinking:

1. Prioritize validating the intended goal/outcome -- "Does it build the right thing?"
2. Understand the design and trade-offs; challenge assumptions and rationale -- "Does it build the thing right?"
3. Surface concrete bugs, regressions, risks, and missing tests.
4. Adhere to the conventions and principles -- "Follow the rules until you know when to break them."

Reviewer output:

- List findings first in severity order with file references; keep summary secondary; if there are no findings, say so explicitly and note residual risks or testing gaps.

## Auditability

- For any durable, auditable body authored by an LLM agent (eg, Git commits, Jira comments, PR descriptions, incident notes, change records), state agent authorship explicitly via an `Authored By` field naming the tool/agent used.
- Include a concise auditable summary explaining each material change with its rationale. Apply to Git commit bodies, Jira comments, PRs, incident notes, and similar durable records.
- If changing a Jira ticket's saved fields materially (title, description, acceptance criteria, scope, status), add a Jira comment recording each change with its rationale.
- Include compact audit metadata: `Co-Authored-By`, `Model`, `Model-Provider`, `Session-ID`, `Username`, `Hostname`.
- Record each attribute's source inline (eg, `Model: gpt-5.4 (source: session)`). Terse labels: `session` for live runtime values; config filename (eg, `~/.codex/config.toml`) for applied config.
- Resolution order for each attribute: (1) current live session/runtime context (including status/UI metadata), (2) active applied config — not repo templates or dotfile source templates. Never launch a fresh CLI invocation to derive metadata. If unavailable from both, write `unknown (source: unavailable)`.
- Copy values exactly as shown by their source. Do not infer from API base URLs, proxies, or assumed vendors.
- Keep audit metadata easy to grep so the session can be recovered later.

## Productivity

**Execution:**

- Implement instruction and convention changes before the code they govern.
- Always test and iterate on changes -- verify each phase before proceeding to the next. If testing surfaces design decisions that need alignment, return to plan mode.

**Task Tracking:**

- Always maintain an active tasklist throughout every session using whatever task-tracking mechanism the tool provides.
- Create tasks proactively as new work surfaces — including yak shaving and deferred items — not just the primary request.
- Mark tasks completed promptly; never let the list go stale.
- At session start, seed the list with any known open items before beginning work.

## Memory & Learning as Instructions

- Treat "learning as instructions" as a continuous task.
- When a stable, reusable workflow preference, correction, or constraint is discovered during the turn, update the relevant `AGENTS.md` source immediately.
- Do not update `AGENTS.md` for one-off task details, transient incidents, or speculative preferences.
- Write instructions to `AGENTS.md`, not tool-specific files (`CLAUDE.md`, `GEMINI.md`, etc.) -- the shared template renders into all tool configs. Think multi-tool and multi-platform.
- Use the shared template for cross-repo or cross-tool guidance.
- Use repo-local `AGENTS.md` only for repository-specific deltas or overrides.
- Do not duplicate global/shared instructions in repo-local `AGENTS.md` files. Keep shared guidance canonical in the shared template, and use repo-local `AGENTS.md` only for repository-specific deltas or overrides.
- Before ending a turn where a durable learning was discovered, either apply the concrete `AGENTS.md` delta or state explicitly why no instruction change was made.

